1
00:00:46,000 --> 00:00:47,360
That's right.

2
00:00:48,400 --> 00:00:49,600
New York.

3
00:00:50,320 --> 00:00:51,960
It's 1958.

4
00:00:53,680 --> 00:00:56,240
Anyway, for a few more minutes it is.

5
00:00:57,200 --> 00:01:00,240
Come midnight, it's going to be 1959.

6
00:01:01,000 --> 00:01:03,200
A whole other feeling.

7
00:01:03,240 --> 00:01:04,720
The New Year.

8
00:01:05,520 --> 00:01:06,720
The future.

9
00:01:08,010 --> 00:01:11,810
Old Daddy Earth fixing to start
one more trip around the sun.

10
00:01:12,570 --> 00:01:15,690
Everybody hoping this ride round
be a little more giddy...

11
00:01:16,490 --> 00:01:17,890
...a little more gay.

12
00:01:18,610 --> 00:01:22,010
All over town, champagne corks
is a-popping.

13
00:01:22,970 --> 00:01:27,530
Over in the Waldorf, the big shots is
dancing to the strains of Guy Lombardo.

14
00:01:28,850 --> 00:01:33,690
In Times Square, the little folks is watching
and waiting for that big ball to drop.

15
00:01:35,290 --> 00:01:38,730
They're all trying to catch hold
of one moment of time...

16
00:01:39,330 --> 00:01:40,770
...to be able to say:

17
00:01:41,010 --> 00:01:42,770
"Right now! This is it!

18
00:01:43,610 --> 00:01:44,650
I got it!"

19
00:01:46,810 --> 00:01:48,770
Of course, by then it'll be past.

20
00:01:49,370 --> 00:01:50,970
But they're all happy...

21
00:01:51,730 --> 00:01:53,730
...everybody having a good time.

22
00:01:54,770 --> 00:01:56,290
Well, almost everybody.

23
00:01:57,610 --> 00:02:00,610
There's a few lost souls
floating around out there.

24
00:02:02,970 --> 00:02:05,090
Now, if y'all ain't from the city...

25
00:02:05,530 --> 00:02:07,970
...we got something here
called "the rat race".

26
00:02:09,060 --> 00:02:13,060
Got a way of chewing folks up
so that they don't want no celebrating...

27
00:02:13,460 --> 00:02:15,260
...don't want no cheering up.

28
00:02:15,620 --> 00:02:17,860
Don't care nothing about no New Year's.

29
00:02:18,900 --> 00:02:20,060
Out of hope...

30
00:02:20,340 --> 00:02:21,620
...out of rope...

31
00:02:21,780 --> 00:02:23,020
...out of time.

32
00:02:24,660 --> 00:02:26,580
This here is Norville Barnes.

33
00:02:28,420 --> 00:02:30,300
That office he's stepping out of...

34
00:02:30,380 --> 00:02:33,460
...is the office of the president
of Hudsucker Industries.

35
00:02:34,140 --> 00:02:35,460
That's his office.

36
00:02:36,860 --> 00:02:38,420
How'd he get so high?

37
00:02:39,380 --> 00:02:41,340
And why's he feeling so low?

38
00:02:43,060 --> 00:02:44,780
Is he really going to do it?

39
00:02:45,460 --> 00:02:48,620
Is Norville really going
to jelly up the sidewalk?

40
00:02:50,260 --> 00:02:51,620
Well, the future...

41
00:02:52,100 --> 00:02:54,660
...that's something you can
never tell about.

42
00:02:55,780 --> 00:02:56,980
But the past...

43
00:02:59,300 --> 00:03:00,900
...that's another story.

44
00:05:17,530 --> 00:05:19,970
So in the third quarter
we saw no signs of weakening.

45
00:05:20,050 --> 00:05:23,370
We're up 18%%% over last year's
third-quarter gross...

46
00:05:23,610 --> 00:05:25,970
...and that, needless to say,
is a new record.

47
00:05:26,050 --> 00:05:30,370
Our competition continues to flag
and we continue to take up the slack.

48
00:05:30,810 --> 00:05:33,330
Market shares in most divisions
is increasing...

49
00:05:33,410 --> 00:05:36,330
...and we have opened
seven new regional offices.

50
00:05:36,770 --> 00:05:38,210
Our international division...

51
00:05:38,290 --> 00:05:42,330
...is also showing vigorous signs of upward
movement for the last six months...

52
00:05:42,490 --> 00:05:45,570
...and we're looking
at some exciting things in R&D.

53
00:06:24,100 --> 00:06:27,420
Sub-franchising. Don't talk to me
about sub-franchising.

54
00:06:27,580 --> 00:06:29,860
We're making so much money
in sub-franchising...

55
00:06:29,940 --> 00:06:31,500
...it isn't even funny.

56
00:06:31,780 --> 00:06:35,820
Our nominees and assigns continue
to multiply and expand...

57
00:06:35,900 --> 00:06:39,420
...extending our influence nationally
and abroad.

58
00:06:39,580 --> 00:06:41,940
Our owned and operateds are performing...

59
00:06:41,980 --> 00:06:45,100
...far beyond our expectations
both here and abroad.

60
00:06:45,220 --> 00:06:47,700
And the Federal Tax Act of 1958...

61
00:06:47,900 --> 00:06:51,500
...is giving us a swell write-off
on our plant and heavies.

62
00:07:15,830 --> 00:07:19,510
And our last debenture issue
was this year's fastest seller.

63
00:07:20,030 --> 00:07:22,390
So, third quarter and year-to-date...

64
00:07:22,630 --> 00:07:26,550
...we have set a new record in sales,
a new record in gross...

65
00:07:26,630 --> 00:07:29,150
...a new record in pre-tax earnings...

66
00:07:29,350 --> 00:07:32,110
...a new record in after-tax profits...

67
00:07:32,350 --> 00:07:35,150
...and our stock has split twice
in the past year.

68
00:07:35,510 --> 00:07:36,550
In short...

69
00:07:41,110 --> 00:07:42,470
...we're loaded.

70
00:08:33,120 --> 00:08:34,560
Mr. Hudsucker?

71
00:10:15,780 --> 00:10:18,180
It's a pity to waste a whole Monte Cristo.

72
00:10:19,060 --> 00:10:20,540
He could've opened the window.

73
00:10:20,620 --> 00:10:23,380
Waring Hudsucker never did anything
the easy way.

74
00:10:23,940 --> 00:10:26,900
Why? Why did he do it?
Everything was going so well.

75
00:10:27,700 --> 00:10:30,500
What am I, a headshrinker?
Maybe the man was unhappy.

76
00:10:30,660 --> 00:10:32,340
He didn't look unhappy.

77
00:10:32,500 --> 00:10:36,300
-He didn't look rich.
-He was never an easy man to figure out.

78
00:10:36,820 --> 00:10:39,340
He built this company with his bare hands.

79
00:10:39,980 --> 00:10:42,100
Every step he took was a step up...

80
00:10:43,140 --> 00:10:44,900
...except, of course, this last one.

81
00:10:44,980 --> 00:10:46,860
He was a swell fella...

82
00:10:47,660 --> 00:10:51,420
...but when the president, chairman
and owner of 87% of the stock...

83
00:10:51,500 --> 00:10:52,580
...drops...

84
00:10:53,220 --> 00:10:54,260
...44 floors...

85
00:10:54,340 --> 00:10:55,060
45.

86
00:10:55,140 --> 00:10:56,420
Counting the mezzanine.

87
00:10:56,580 --> 00:10:59,220
Then the company, too, has a problem.
Stillson!

88
00:11:01,380 --> 00:11:03,860
What exactly is the disposition
of Waring's stock?

89
00:11:04,020 --> 00:11:05,300
As you know...

90
00:11:05,380 --> 00:11:07,540
...Hud left no will and no family.

91
00:11:07,620 --> 00:11:10,580
The company bylaws are quite clear
in that event.

92
00:11:10,660 --> 00:11:13,940
"His entire portfolio will be converted
into common stock...

93
00:11:14,100 --> 00:11:18,270
"...and will be sold over the counter
as of the first of the fiscal year...

94
00:11:18,390 --> 00:11:20,390
-"...following his demise".
-Meaning?

95
00:11:20,750 --> 00:11:24,270
Meaning simply that Waring's stock
and control of the company...

96
00:11:24,390 --> 00:11:27,390
...will be made available
to the public January 1st.

97
00:11:29,070 --> 00:11:30,470
Do you mean to say...

98
00:11:30,670 --> 00:11:34,110
...that any slob in a smelly T-shirt
will be able to buy Hudsucker stock?

99
00:11:34,430 --> 00:11:36,430
The company bylaws are quite clear.

100
00:11:36,510 --> 00:11:38,470
My God! You're animals!

101
00:11:38,550 --> 00:11:42,630
How can you discuss his stock
when the man has just leapt 45 floors?

102
00:11:42,670 --> 00:11:43,510
44.

103
00:11:43,590 --> 00:11:45,150
Not counting the mezzanine.

104
00:11:45,230 --> 00:11:46,350
Quit showboating.

105
00:11:46,390 --> 00:11:48,750
The man is gone. The question now
is whether we'll let...

106
00:11:48,790 --> 00:11:51,710
...John Q. Public waltz in here
and buy our company.

107
00:11:51,790 --> 00:11:53,750
What are you suggesting?

108
00:11:53,830 --> 00:11:56,710
Certainly we can't afford
to buy a controlling interest.

109
00:11:56,950 --> 00:11:58,950
Not while the stock is this strong.

110
00:11:59,950 --> 00:12:02,270
How soon before Hud's paper
hits the market?

111
00:12:02,350 --> 00:12:03,150
January 1st.

112
00:12:03,190 --> 00:12:04,550
-Thirty days.
-Four weeks.

113
00:12:04,590 --> 00:12:06,510
-A month at the most.
-One month...

114
00:12:06,590 --> 00:12:08,750
...to make the blue-chip investment
of the century...

115
00:12:08,830 --> 00:12:10,990
...look like a round-trip ticket
on the Titanic.

116
00:12:11,030 --> 00:12:13,670
We play up the fact that Hud is dead.

117
00:12:13,750 --> 00:12:15,150
Long live the Hud!

118
00:12:15,230 --> 00:12:16,270
We depress the stock.

119
00:12:16,350 --> 00:12:19,000
-To the point where we can buy 50%.
-51%.

120
00:12:19,040 --> 00:12:20,360
Not counting the mezzanine.

121
00:12:20,440 --> 00:12:21,360
It could work.

122
00:12:21,440 --> 00:12:22,840
-It should work.
-It would work.

123
00:12:22,880 --> 00:12:24,520
It's working already.

124
00:12:25,680 --> 00:12:28,520
Waring Hudsucker is abstract art
on Madison Avenue.

125
00:12:29,640 --> 00:12:33,880
What we need now is a new president
who will inspire panic in the stockholder.

126
00:12:34,040 --> 00:12:35,400
-A puppet!
-A proxy!

127
00:12:35,480 --> 00:12:36,400
A pawn!

128
00:12:38,840 --> 00:12:39,920
Some jerk...

129
00:12:40,520 --> 00:12:42,320
...we can really push around.

130
00:12:44,200 --> 00:12:47,800
You punch in at 8:30 every a.m.,
at 7:30 a.m. following a business holiday...

131
00:12:47,840 --> 00:12:49,840
...unless it's a Monday, then it's 8:00.

132
00:12:49,920 --> 00:12:53,400
-Punch in late and they dock you.
-This goes to seven! Urgent.

133
00:12:53,440 --> 00:12:57,000
Incoming articles get a voucher.
Outgoing articles provide a voucher.

134
00:12:57,080 --> 00:12:59,400
Move any article without a voucher,
they dock you!

135
00:12:59,480 --> 00:13:01,800
Take this up to the secretarial pool
on three! ASAP!

136
00:13:01,880 --> 00:13:04,440
Letter-size, a green voucher!
Folder-size, a yellow voucher!

137
00:13:04,480 --> 00:13:06,000
Parcel-size, a maroon voucher!

138
00:13:06,080 --> 00:13:08,080
This is for Morgatross! Chop-chop!

139
00:13:08,120 --> 00:13:10,280
Wrong color voucher and they dock you!

140
00:13:11,120 --> 00:13:13,480
6-7-8-7-0-4-9-Alpha-6!

141
00:13:13,760 --> 00:13:16,760
That is your employee number!
It will not be repeated!

142
00:13:16,960 --> 00:13:19,370
Without it, you can't cash your paycheck.

143
00:13:19,450 --> 00:13:21,090
All right! This goes up to 27!

144
00:13:21,170 --> 00:13:24,010
Return a waiver!
Do not return without a signed waiver!

145
00:13:24,090 --> 00:13:28,050
Inter-office mail is code 37!
Intra-office mail is 37-3.

146
00:13:28,210 --> 00:13:30,370
Outside mail is 3-37.

147
00:13:30,530 --> 00:13:32,250
Code it wrong and they dock you!

148
00:13:32,290 --> 00:13:35,050
I was supposed to have this on 28
ten minutes ago!

149
00:13:35,370 --> 00:13:39,770
This has been your orientation.
Is there anything you do not understand?

150
00:13:39,970 --> 00:13:43,330
If you have not been fully orientated,
you must file a complaint!

151
00:13:43,410 --> 00:13:46,250
File a faulty complaint, and they dock you!

152
00:13:51,570 --> 00:13:52,530
Kloppitt.

153
00:13:52,690 --> 00:13:55,490
Kloppitt, Kloppitt, Kloppitt, Kloppitt....

154
00:13:55,530 --> 00:13:56,930
Max Kloppitt.

155
00:13:57,010 --> 00:13:59,170
"Max Kloppitt, Jr".

156
00:14:07,410 --> 00:14:10,530
What do you do when the envelope
is too big for the slot?

157
00:14:11,810 --> 00:14:13,970
If you fold them, they fire you.

158
00:14:16,090 --> 00:14:17,570
I usually throw them out.

159
00:14:23,900 --> 00:14:25,340
Just got hired today.

160
00:14:25,820 --> 00:14:26,700
Terrific.

161
00:14:27,460 --> 00:14:28,420
Entry level.

162
00:14:31,420 --> 00:14:32,380
But...

163
00:14:33,020 --> 00:14:34,380
...I got big ideas.

164
00:14:35,060 --> 00:14:36,340
I'm sure you do.

165
00:14:36,820 --> 00:14:37,980
For instance...

166
00:14:39,100 --> 00:14:40,300
...look at this sweet baby.

167
00:14:44,060 --> 00:14:45,500
I developed it myself.

168
00:14:45,580 --> 00:14:47,900
Yes, sirree, this is my ticket upstairs.

169
00:14:51,420 --> 00:14:52,780
You know, for kids.

170
00:14:53,740 --> 00:14:54,660
Terrific.

171
00:14:55,740 --> 00:14:58,620
So, you see. I won't be working
in the mail room long.

172
00:14:58,700 --> 00:15:00,540
No, I don't guess you will be.

173
00:15:01,740 --> 00:15:03,260
How long've you been here?

174
00:15:03,340 --> 00:15:04,540
Forty-eight years.

175
00:15:05,020 --> 00:15:07,260
Next year they move me up to parcels...

176
00:15:08,300 --> 00:15:09,580
...if I'm lucky.

177
00:15:11,740 --> 00:15:13,580
Attention Hudsucker employees:

178
00:15:13,980 --> 00:15:17,620
We regretfully announce
that at 30 seconds after the hour of noon...

179
00:15:17,740 --> 00:15:18,940
...Hudsucker time...

180
00:15:19,020 --> 00:15:21,590
...Waring Hudsucker, Founder, President...

181
00:15:21,830 --> 00:15:24,630
...and Chairman of the Board
of Hudsucker Industries...

182
00:15:24,710 --> 00:15:26,150
...merged with the infinite.

183
00:15:26,430 --> 00:15:28,790
To mark this occasion of corporate loss...

184
00:15:28,870 --> 00:15:32,830
...we ask that all employees observe
a moment of silent contemplation.

185
00:15:39,670 --> 00:15:41,550
Thank you for your kind attention.

186
00:15:41,750 --> 00:15:44,630
This moment has been duly noted
on your timecards...

187
00:15:44,750 --> 00:15:47,830
...and will be deducted from your pay.
That is all.

188
00:15:51,070 --> 00:15:52,230
Blue letter!

189
00:15:52,390 --> 00:15:53,510
Blue letter!

190
00:15:53,590 --> 00:15:55,270
They're bringing a blue letter!

191
00:16:28,000 --> 00:16:29,400
It's a blue letter.

192
00:16:30,160 --> 00:16:31,360
Top, top level.

193
00:16:32,040 --> 00:16:34,400
Confidential communication
between the brass.

194
00:16:35,320 --> 00:16:36,640
Usually bad news.

195
00:16:37,520 --> 00:16:39,360
They hate blue letters upstairs.

196
00:16:43,360 --> 00:16:44,360
Hate them.

197
00:16:44,440 --> 00:16:45,240
You!

198
00:16:45,760 --> 00:16:47,120
Yeah, you! Barnes!

199
00:16:47,680 --> 00:16:48,880
You don't look busy!

200
00:16:49,440 --> 00:16:51,400
Think you can handle a blue letter?

201
00:16:51,480 --> 00:16:55,920
This letter was sent this morning
by the big man himself, Waring Hudsucker!

202
00:16:56,160 --> 00:16:59,600
It's addressed to Sid Mussburger,
Hudsucker's right-hand man!

203
00:16:59,760 --> 00:17:01,200
It's a blue letter!

204
00:17:01,600 --> 00:17:04,480
That means you got to put it right
in Mussburger's hands.

205
00:17:04,640 --> 00:17:06,840
No secretaries! No receptionists!

206
00:17:07,040 --> 00:17:09,200
No colleagues! No excuses!

207
00:17:10,120 --> 00:17:11,280
Mussburger!

208
00:17:13,120 --> 00:17:17,120
Hi! My name's Buzz, I got the fuzz,
I make the elevator do what she does.

209
00:17:17,880 --> 00:17:19,040
Hang it up to dry.

210
00:17:19,120 --> 00:17:20,960
-What's your pleasure?
-Fourty-four.

211
00:17:21,120 --> 00:17:23,930
Forty-four, the top-brass floor.
Say, buddy...

212
00:17:24,090 --> 00:17:27,690
...what takes 50 years to get to
the top floor and 30 seconds to get down?

213
00:17:27,930 --> 00:17:30,090
Waring Hudsucker! You get it, buddy?

214
00:17:30,410 --> 00:17:33,610
Say, buddy! Mr. Kline, up to nine.
Mrs. Dell, Personnel.

215
00:17:33,730 --> 00:17:35,610
-Mr. Levin, 37.
-Thirty-six.

216
00:17:35,690 --> 00:17:36,730
Walk down!

217
00:17:36,810 --> 00:17:38,490
Ladies and gentlemen,
please step to the rear.

218
00:17:38,570 --> 00:17:40,570
Here comes the gargantuan Mr. Grier.

219
00:17:42,850 --> 00:17:46,010
Buddy, who's the most liquid businessman
on the street?

220
00:17:46,090 --> 00:17:47,370
Waring Hudsucker.

221
00:17:48,010 --> 00:17:51,490
When is the sidewalk fully dressed?
When it's wearing Hudsucker!

222
00:17:52,690 --> 00:17:53,610
You get it?

223
00:17:53,690 --> 00:17:57,010
It's a pun, a knee-slapper,
a play on Jesus, Joseph and Mary....

224
00:17:57,130 --> 00:17:58,530
Is that a blue letter?

225
00:17:58,570 --> 00:18:02,570
Why didn't you tell a guy? Hold on, folks,
we're express to the top floor!

226
00:18:17,330 --> 00:18:18,610
Good luck, buddy.

227
00:18:21,810 --> 00:18:23,050
You'll need it.

228
00:18:35,460 --> 00:18:37,060
Mr. Mussburger's office?

229
00:19:32,070 --> 00:19:33,070
Hello.

230
00:19:33,990 --> 00:19:36,230
Do you have an appointment?

231
00:19:37,830 --> 00:19:39,790
Shall we look in the book?

232
00:19:41,950 --> 00:19:44,670
-We don't seem to be in the book.
-I wouldn't be.

233
00:19:44,830 --> 00:19:48,310
If we had an appointment,
we'd be in the book.

234
00:19:48,830 --> 00:19:49,990
I have this....

235
00:19:50,550 --> 00:19:51,750
Oh, here it is.

236
00:19:57,310 --> 00:19:58,230
Gambotz?

237
00:19:59,110 --> 00:20:00,310
Harry Gambotz?

238
00:20:00,510 --> 00:20:02,990
No, too risky.
He's green but he's not slow.

239
00:20:04,470 --> 00:20:05,470
Who is he?

240
00:20:05,790 --> 00:20:08,550
No, I want an imbecile,
not a cipher, or you'd have the job.

241
00:20:10,910 --> 00:20:12,670
They moved him to grommets and O-rings.

242
00:20:12,710 --> 00:20:14,070
He's doing pretty well.

243
00:20:15,390 --> 00:20:16,990
No, not McClanahan.

244
00:20:17,950 --> 00:20:20,870
He bungled the Teleyard merger
so he's got something to prove.

245
00:20:21,150 --> 00:20:22,390
Who let you in?

246
00:20:23,070 --> 00:20:26,000
Atwater? Tremendous.
Except I just fired him last week.

247
00:20:26,680 --> 00:20:27,800
Mr. Mussburger...

248
00:20:27,880 --> 00:20:29,800
...Mr. Bumstead's waiting downstairs.

249
00:20:29,920 --> 00:20:32,040
-I'll be right there.
-Yes, Mr. Mussburger.

250
00:20:32,080 --> 00:20:33,160
Spit it out!

251
00:20:35,120 --> 00:20:37,480
Maybe you're
the company's biggest moron.

252
00:20:37,720 --> 00:20:41,200
We can't use Morris. Been here too long.
He's a nice guy with too many friends.

253
00:20:41,280 --> 00:20:44,160
In fact, why don't you fire him?
Scratch that, I'll fire him.

254
00:20:44,720 --> 00:20:46,160
Make it fast. Fast!

255
00:20:46,640 --> 00:20:48,520
Mr. Bumstead is growing restless.

256
00:20:48,600 --> 00:20:50,960
Tell him I'll be right there.
Give him a magazine.

257
00:20:51,040 --> 00:20:52,480
What are you, a mute?

258
00:20:54,120 --> 00:20:55,400
How's the stock?

259
00:20:55,520 --> 00:20:57,520
Bad? Well, it's not bad enough.

260
00:20:58,160 --> 00:20:59,280
Listen, chump.

261
00:20:59,360 --> 00:21:03,400
Either you find me a ding-dong or tender
your key to the executive washroom.

262
00:21:03,480 --> 00:21:06,200
That goes double for you, pal.
Earclay? Oodgay!

263
00:21:10,760 --> 00:21:13,040
This better be good. I'm in a bad mood.

264
00:21:14,120 --> 00:21:17,440
Sir, I've got something for you
from the mail room, but first...

265
00:21:17,480 --> 00:21:22,320
...if I could take a minute of your very
valuable time to show you something...

266
00:21:22,400 --> 00:21:25,360
...I've been working on
for the past two or three years.

267
00:21:32,450 --> 00:21:33,810
You know, for kids.

268
00:21:34,650 --> 00:21:37,490
It's perfect for Hudsucker,
not that I'm any great genius.

269
00:21:37,530 --> 00:21:41,530
They say inspiration is 99% perspiration
and in my case it's at least twice that...

270
00:21:41,610 --> 00:21:44,490
-...but I've got to tell you, sir...
-Wait a minute!

271
00:22:27,250 --> 00:22:28,420
Sit down, son.

272
00:22:31,220 --> 00:22:32,180
Go ahead.

273
00:22:34,020 --> 00:22:35,060
Try it on.

274
00:22:48,060 --> 00:22:49,340
Put your feet up.

275
00:22:53,100 --> 00:22:54,060
Go ahead.

276
00:22:56,180 --> 00:22:58,500
Let's get to know one another, shall we?

277
00:23:00,380 --> 00:23:01,500
Let's chat...

278
00:23:04,740 --> 00:23:05,740
...man-to-man.

279
00:23:12,740 --> 00:23:14,980
You're from the basement, aren't you?

280
00:23:16,140 --> 00:23:18,100
And weren't blessed with much...

281
00:23:20,220 --> 00:23:21,340
...education?

282
00:23:21,740 --> 00:23:23,940
Well, I am a college graduate.

283
00:23:24,420 --> 00:23:26,900
But you did not excel in your studies.

284
00:23:26,980 --> 00:23:28,830
Well, I made the dean's list...

285
00:23:29,830 --> 00:23:32,270
...at the Muncie College
of Business Administration.

286
00:23:33,630 --> 00:23:36,270
And your friends called you "jerk",
didn't they?

287
00:23:37,830 --> 00:23:38,750
"Dope?"

288
00:23:38,870 --> 00:23:39,750
"Dipstick?"

289
00:23:39,790 --> 00:23:41,230
"Lamebrain?" "Schmo?"

290
00:23:41,310 --> 00:23:42,510
Not even behind your back?

291
00:23:42,590 --> 00:23:45,070
They voted me "Most Likely to Succeed".

292
00:23:45,150 --> 00:23:46,310
You're fired.

293
00:23:48,470 --> 00:23:51,670
Get your feet off my desk,
get out of my office.

294
00:23:52,230 --> 00:23:53,830
Leave your apron in the locker room.

295
00:23:54,350 --> 00:23:55,310
Oh, my God!

296
00:23:55,430 --> 00:23:59,630
The Bumstead contracts. I've been
working on that deal for four years!

297
00:23:59,790 --> 00:24:01,790
Get out of here! I'll take care of it!

298
00:24:02,630 --> 00:24:05,710
You could have destroyed
the most sensitive document of my career.

299
00:24:05,790 --> 00:24:08,190
Mr. Bumstead is threatening to leave.

300
00:24:08,310 --> 00:24:09,590
I'm on my way down.

301
00:24:09,670 --> 00:24:12,990
We need the first page of the contract
retyped with copies going to Legal.

302
00:24:13,070 --> 00:24:14,590
Yes, Mr. Mussburger.

303
00:24:18,310 --> 00:24:19,790
Out! Out of the office!

304
00:24:22,470 --> 00:24:23,630
Down three points?

305
00:24:23,710 --> 00:24:26,030
That's encouraging. How about New York?

306
00:24:27,150 --> 00:24:28,910
Not that way, through the door!

307
00:24:29,560 --> 00:24:32,200
It'll take three hours to retype
the Bumstead contracts.

308
00:24:32,240 --> 00:24:33,320
Where are you going?

309
00:24:33,400 --> 00:24:35,040
Get out! Stop that!

310
00:24:35,320 --> 00:24:36,840
Mr. Bumstead's threatening to leave.

311
00:24:36,920 --> 00:24:39,360
Not the whole contract, just the first page.

312
00:24:39,640 --> 00:24:41,640
I'll be there. Give him another magazine.

313
00:24:41,680 --> 00:24:44,240
-He says he'll leave.
-I said I'll be there!

314
00:24:45,320 --> 00:24:48,760
Up on your feet! We don't crawl here
at Hudsucker Industries!

315
00:24:49,160 --> 00:24:50,920
-My leg is on fire!
-No assumptions!

316
00:24:50,960 --> 00:24:54,520
It's early yet. Just let me know
where we stand at the closing bell.

317
00:25:03,600 --> 00:25:05,720
Oh, my God, the Bumstead contracts!

318
00:25:10,960 --> 00:25:12,840
No magazines! No coffee!

319
00:25:13,040 --> 00:25:17,400
Mussburger! I want to see Mussburger!
Or did he jump out a window too?

320
00:25:18,440 --> 00:25:21,920
Don't worry, Mr. Mussburger, I got you!
I got you by your pants.

321
00:25:24,720 --> 00:25:25,600
Pants?

322
00:25:30,000 --> 00:25:33,770
Mr. Mussburger, I'm gonna give
your pants a nice double stitch.

323
00:25:34,210 --> 00:25:37,810
It'll make them real strong
and you're going to look real sharp.

324
00:25:38,650 --> 00:25:41,050
No. Single stitch is fine.

325
00:25:41,250 --> 00:25:43,490
But the double stitch lasts forever.

326
00:25:44,650 --> 00:25:47,130
Why on earth would I want
a double stitch?

327
00:25:48,370 --> 00:25:49,770
To pad your account.

328
00:25:50,170 --> 00:25:51,650
Single stitch is fine.

329
00:25:57,730 --> 00:25:58,770
Damn!

330
00:26:05,130 --> 00:26:08,330
What the heck! Mr. Mussburger
is such a nice man...

331
00:26:08,690 --> 00:26:11,170
...I'm going to give him
a double stitch anyway.

332
00:26:12,250 --> 00:26:15,450
That's some strong stitch, you bet!

333
00:27:57,510 --> 00:27:59,550
"The Einstein of Enterprise".

334
00:28:00,550 --> 00:28:01,990
"The Edison of Industry".

335
00:28:03,190 --> 00:28:05,270
"The Billion-Dollar Cranium! "

336
00:28:07,070 --> 00:28:08,550
"Idea Man! "

337
00:28:10,350 --> 00:28:12,590
And not one of you has given me
a story on him!

338
00:28:12,630 --> 00:28:14,310
Bunch of lamebrains!

339
00:28:14,750 --> 00:28:17,310
Facts, figures, charts.
They never sold a newspaper!

340
00:28:17,470 --> 00:28:19,350
I read this morning's Argus
and let me tell you something:

341
00:28:19,430 --> 00:28:20,950
I'd wrap a fish in it!

342
00:28:21,030 --> 00:28:22,590
I'd use it as kindling!

343
00:28:22,670 --> 00:28:26,870
I'd train my poodle on it if he wasn't
a French poodle and partial to Paris Soir.

344
00:28:27,030 --> 00:28:29,790
But I wouldn't pay a nickel
to read the thing!

345
00:28:29,870 --> 00:28:31,830
Come on, Chief, give us a break.

346
00:28:32,430 --> 00:28:34,440
Sure, Tibbs. Take a break.

347
00:28:35,160 --> 00:28:37,200
Go to Florida. Lie in the sun.

348
00:28:37,800 --> 00:28:40,160
Wait for a coconut to drop.
File a story on it.

349
00:28:40,480 --> 00:28:43,640
It'd be more of a grabber than your piece
on the county grain surplus!

350
00:28:43,720 --> 00:28:46,120
The human angle!
That's what sells papers!

351
00:28:46,480 --> 00:28:49,800
We need a front page with a heart
and the ldea Man can put it there!

352
00:28:49,880 --> 00:28:51,280
If we had more access...

353
00:28:51,320 --> 00:28:53,720
If a frog had wings
it wouldn't bump it's ass hopping.

354
00:28:53,800 --> 00:28:55,760
I don't want excuses, I want results!

355
00:28:56,160 --> 00:28:58,720
What makes the ldea Man tick?
Where's he from?

356
00:28:58,840 --> 00:29:02,280
I want to know everything about him!
Has he got a girl? Has he got parents?

357
00:29:02,360 --> 00:29:04,320
Everybody has parents.

358
00:29:04,480 --> 00:29:06,080
All right, how many?

359
00:29:07,160 --> 00:29:09,320
How about it, Parkinson?
You've been awfully quiet.

360
00:29:11,200 --> 00:29:12,600
Still waters run deep.

361
00:29:12,680 --> 00:29:15,080
Only thing deep with Parkinson
are the holes in his ears.

362
00:29:15,160 --> 00:29:16,720
Yes! ldea Man!

363
00:29:17,320 --> 00:29:20,440
What are his hopes and dreams,
his desires and aspirations?

364
00:29:20,720 --> 00:29:23,320
Does he think all the time
or a certain portion of the day?

365
00:29:23,360 --> 00:29:26,800
How tall is he? Where does he sleep?
What does he have for breakfast?

366
00:29:26,840 --> 00:29:29,000
Does he put jam on his toast
or doesn't he?

367
00:29:29,080 --> 00:29:31,040
If not, why not and since when?

368
00:29:32,000 --> 00:29:32,960
Well?

369
00:29:34,250 --> 00:29:35,730
You're useless.

370
00:29:36,450 --> 00:29:37,650
Yes. Idea Man.

371
00:29:38,290 --> 00:29:39,250
"Creator".

372
00:29:39,330 --> 00:29:40,330
"Innovator".

373
00:29:40,610 --> 00:29:41,890
"Cerebrator".

374
00:29:42,530 --> 00:29:43,530
Fake!

375
00:29:44,130 --> 00:29:46,090
I tell you, the guy's a phony.

376
00:29:46,170 --> 00:29:47,610
-Phony?
-As a $3 bill.

377
00:29:47,690 --> 00:29:49,290
-Says who?
-Says me, Amy Archer!

378
00:29:49,370 --> 00:29:51,610
Why is he an ldea Man?
Because Hudsucker says so?

379
00:29:51,650 --> 00:29:54,170
What are his ideas?
Why can't anyone interview him?

380
00:29:54,250 --> 00:29:56,250
Five bucks says she mentions her Pulitzer.

381
00:29:57,090 --> 00:29:58,970
Again? You're on.

382
00:29:59,050 --> 00:30:00,930
Look at the mug on this guy.

383
00:30:00,970 --> 00:30:04,010
The jutting eyebrows, the simian forehead,
the idiotic grin.

384
00:30:04,090 --> 00:30:05,890
He has a face only a mother could love...

385
00:30:07,250 --> 00:30:08,210
...on payday.

386
00:30:08,450 --> 00:30:11,290
The only story here is
how this guy made a monkey out of you.

387
00:30:11,330 --> 00:30:13,850
Like it or not, I'm still editor of this rag.

388
00:30:14,050 --> 00:30:17,010
I thought you were writing,
"J. Edgar Hoover: When Will He Marry?"

389
00:30:17,090 --> 00:30:20,170
-I filed it yesterday. Nice tie, Earl.
-Well, do a follow-up.

390
00:30:20,290 --> 00:30:22,250
"Hoover: Crimebuster or Pantywaist?"

391
00:30:22,330 --> 00:30:25,410
The rest of you mugs get some brains
and get me that ldea Man story!

392
00:30:27,010 --> 00:30:28,170
He's the bunk.

393
00:30:34,050 --> 00:30:35,820
I'll stake my Pulitzer on it!

394
00:30:38,260 --> 00:30:40,220
Say, buddy, where'd you get the new duds?

395
00:30:40,300 --> 00:30:43,100
Say, buddy, how did Old Bucketbutt
like his blue letter?

396
00:30:43,660 --> 00:30:46,700
Did he bust a gut? Did he die?
Well, hello, Mr. Mussburger.

397
00:30:46,740 --> 00:30:48,140
Lobby, we haven't got all day.

398
00:30:48,180 --> 00:30:49,900
Right away, Mr. Mussburger.

399
00:30:50,020 --> 00:30:51,980
How're you this fine morning, sir?

400
00:30:52,740 --> 00:30:55,020
It's been a pleasure serving you today, sir.

401
00:30:55,060 --> 00:30:57,620
It's been a pleasure serving you too, buddy.

402
00:30:57,780 --> 00:31:01,340
Shouldn't we be a little concerned
with the downward spiral of our stock...

403
00:31:01,420 --> 00:31:02,700
...these past few days?

404
00:31:02,780 --> 00:31:05,340
You're the expert,
but at the Muncie College of Business...

405
00:31:05,420 --> 00:31:07,060
Relax, it's only natural...

406
00:31:07,220 --> 00:31:10,620
...in a period of transition for
the more timid element to run for cover.

407
00:31:10,700 --> 00:31:14,220
Like I said, you're the expert
but do you remember the plan I outlined...

408
00:31:14,300 --> 00:31:17,340
...the day I set fire to your....
The day I was promoted?

409
00:31:17,740 --> 00:31:21,740
I do remember and I was impressed.
But that's all forgotten now.

410
00:31:23,820 --> 00:31:24,940
Thank you, Sid.

411
00:31:25,740 --> 00:31:29,180
The reason I mention it is it requires
such a small capital investment....

412
00:31:29,260 --> 00:31:32,380
-There's a huge potential profit...
-Damn it, where's my car?

413
00:31:32,460 --> 00:31:35,340
...given the demographics boom
of the burgeoning middle-class.

414
00:31:35,420 --> 00:31:39,310
So if you agree, I'd like to bounce the idea
off a few people at lunch.

415
00:31:39,390 --> 00:31:40,350
Sure.

416
00:31:40,590 --> 00:31:44,310
Tell whoever you want.
I'd like to hear about it at some point too.

417
00:31:53,270 --> 00:31:54,550
I got gas, Benny.

418
00:31:56,110 --> 00:31:57,390
Tell me about it.

419
00:31:57,830 --> 00:31:59,990
No kidding, Benny. I got gas.

420
00:32:00,790 --> 00:32:02,190
You get the special?

421
00:32:02,550 --> 00:32:03,630
Far from it.

422
00:32:07,470 --> 00:32:08,670
Enter the dame.

423
00:32:09,430 --> 00:32:11,310
There's one in every story.

424
00:32:11,910 --> 00:32:14,390
Ten bucks says she's looking for a handout.

425
00:32:14,710 --> 00:32:17,470
Twenty bucks says not here,
she don't find one.

426
00:32:18,070 --> 00:32:19,630
She's looking for her mark.

427
00:32:19,710 --> 00:32:20,870
She finds him.

428
00:32:20,950 --> 00:32:23,470
She sits down and orders...

429
00:32:24,790 --> 00:32:26,070
...a light lunch.

430
00:32:26,550 --> 00:32:28,670
How will she pay for this lunch?

431
00:32:29,110 --> 00:32:30,830
She looks through her purse.

432
00:32:31,110 --> 00:32:32,110
No money.

433
00:32:32,550 --> 00:32:34,190
The mark notices.

434
00:32:35,550 --> 00:32:37,200
He's not noticing, Benny.

435
00:32:37,280 --> 00:32:38,640
Maybe he's wise.

436
00:32:39,040 --> 00:32:40,440
He don't look wise.

437
00:32:42,560 --> 00:32:43,720
Plan two.

438
00:32:44,040 --> 00:32:45,760
Here come the waterworks.

439
00:32:46,080 --> 00:32:48,080
-Yellowstone.
-Old Faithful.

440
00:32:48,160 --> 00:32:49,920
Hello, Niagara.

441
00:32:50,360 --> 00:32:51,480
He notices.

442
00:32:51,520 --> 00:32:52,880
She's distressed.

443
00:32:53,120 --> 00:32:54,480
He's concerned.

444
00:32:55,040 --> 00:32:57,040
She explains her predicament.

445
00:32:57,400 --> 00:32:58,360
And....

446
00:32:59,000 --> 00:33:00,920
Enter the light lunch.

447
00:33:02,080 --> 00:33:04,080
She's got other problems, of course.

448
00:33:04,160 --> 00:33:05,960
There's illness in the family.

449
00:33:06,400 --> 00:33:09,160
-Her mother needs an operation.
-Urgently.

450
00:33:09,320 --> 00:33:10,920
-Adenoids.
-No, Benny.

451
00:33:12,200 --> 00:33:13,600
Lumbago.

452
00:33:14,320 --> 00:33:16,560
That gag's got whiskers on it.

453
00:33:17,680 --> 00:33:19,200
He ain't biting, Benny.

454
00:33:19,280 --> 00:33:22,000
-She's losing him, Lou.
-Maybe he's wise.

455
00:33:22,600 --> 00:33:24,240
He don't look wise.

456
00:33:24,800 --> 00:33:27,440
-How does she pull this out?
-He's getting away.

457
00:33:27,520 --> 00:33:29,000
She better think fast.

458
00:33:29,320 --> 00:33:30,600
She isn't.

459
00:33:30,920 --> 00:33:32,320
She is!

460
00:33:33,360 --> 00:33:34,680
She's good, Benny.

461
00:33:35,280 --> 00:33:36,720
She's damn good, Lou.

462
00:33:38,050 --> 00:33:40,050
Can I get you boys anything else?

463
00:33:42,250 --> 00:33:43,370
Bromo.

464
00:33:44,170 --> 00:33:45,250
Bromo.

465
00:33:47,170 --> 00:33:50,770
I'm sorry we had to take the stairs.
It was just that horrible elevator boy!

466
00:33:50,850 --> 00:33:53,810
I can't say how much I appreciate
your listening to my story.

467
00:33:53,890 --> 00:33:58,130
I'm lucky to find someone in this bustling
city with a stout heart and a ready ear.

468
00:33:58,690 --> 00:34:00,890
There I was, travelling
through this great country.

469
00:34:00,970 --> 00:34:03,210
Some I met were kind to me,
others exceedingly cruel.

470
00:34:03,290 --> 00:34:05,610
Traveling by motor bus, rail,
even by thumb....

471
00:34:05,650 --> 00:34:07,010
The couch, please.

472
00:34:07,130 --> 00:34:10,410
Hoarding every dollar, counting
every nickel, pinching every penny.

473
00:34:10,650 --> 00:34:13,250
It's been a long road leading
to the coffee shop downstairs.

474
00:34:13,290 --> 00:34:16,530
Not that I'd trade a day, an hour,
a moment of it for anything.

475
00:34:16,850 --> 00:34:18,370
I don't know what came over me.

476
00:34:18,450 --> 00:34:20,650
I guess it was the shock of eating
after so long...

477
00:34:20,730 --> 00:34:23,010
...without the enzymes kicking in
after so long....

478
00:34:26,970 --> 00:34:30,450
Then you couldn't possibly know
what it is to be tired and hungry.

479
00:34:30,650 --> 00:34:31,650
Hungry, anyway.

480
00:34:31,690 --> 00:34:34,690
I don't want to bore you with details
of my life. It's not happy.

481
00:34:34,770 --> 00:34:37,130
Suffice to say I'm jobless,
but not for want of trying.

482
00:34:37,170 --> 00:34:40,660
I'm friendless, with no one to take care
of me and had you not come along...

483
00:34:40,740 --> 00:34:43,340
-...exactly when you did....
-I, myself...

484
00:34:43,460 --> 00:34:45,340
I arrived in town not ten days ago...

485
00:34:45,420 --> 00:34:48,500
...full of dreams, anxious to make my way
in the world...

486
00:34:48,540 --> 00:34:51,220
...a little naive perhaps,
but armed with determination...

487
00:34:51,300 --> 00:34:53,820
...a solid work ethic,
and an indomitable belief in the future...

488
00:34:53,900 --> 00:34:55,700
-I, myself...
-...only to have that belief...

489
00:34:55,780 --> 00:34:58,980
...that unsullied optimism, dashed against
the marble of the workplace.

490
00:34:59,060 --> 00:35:01,980
Such is life. Seek and ye shall find.
Work and ye shall prosper.

491
00:35:02,060 --> 00:35:03,660
-Cigarette?
-No, thank you.

492
00:35:03,740 --> 00:35:05,980
Seek and ye shall find,
work and ye shall prosper.

493
00:35:06,060 --> 00:35:08,700
These were the watchwords,
the ethos of my education...

494
00:35:08,780 --> 00:35:10,220
...the values instilled in me...

495
00:35:10,260 --> 00:35:13,460
...while I was growing up in a town
you've probably never heard of.

496
00:35:13,540 --> 00:35:15,140
-Mind if I join you?
-Be my guest.

497
00:35:15,220 --> 00:35:17,180
A town you've probably never heard of...

498
00:35:17,260 --> 00:35:20,020
...a dusty crossroads of which
you've probably never heard.

